text: Indian J Microbiol https://doi.org/10.1007/s12088-021-00941-7 The snogI Gene is Necessary for the Proper Functioning of the Nogalamycin Biosynthesis Pathway Received: 26 October 2020 / Accepted: 18 April 2021 (cid:2) Association of Microbiologists of India 2021 Abstract Anthracycline have multifunctional drugs molecular structures, and small changes in the structure of the glycosyls around the chromophore affect their mecha- toxicity, anti-tumor nism of action, pharmacokinetics, activity, and many other signiﬁcant parameters. DnrJ has a similar function to snogI but inverse stereoselectivity. SnogI encoding amino transferase was substituted for DnrJ for the purpose of obtaining nogalamycin analogues. We inactivated the snogI gene encoding an aminotransferase responsible for the formation of nogalamine and introduced the dnrJ gene encoding an aminotransferase responsible for the formation of daunosamine. We obtained the recombi- nant strain mLMX-3-100, in which the production of nogalamycin was disrupted. Interestingly, contrary to our predictions, no epi-nogalamycin was produced; neverthe- the snogI gene is less, necessary for the proper functioning of the nogalamycin biosynthesis pathway. Keywords Nogalamycin (cid:2) In situ displacement (cid:2) Combinatorial biosynthesis (cid:2) dnrJ (cid:2) snogI Anthracycline antibiotics comprise a group of natural products that possess important pharmacological efﬁcacies and diverse structures [1]. Their prominent anticancer activity makes them commercially valuable and as such, they are one of the most deeply studied groups of natural products discovered over the past 50 years [2]. Nogala- mycin is similar to other natural anthracycline antibiotics (daunorubicin, carminomycin, and aclacinomycin) pro- duced by microbes, which are of great importance since their derivatives are widely used in cancer chemotherapy [3]. Their biosynthesis begins with the anthracene ring skeleton, which is biocatalysed by polyketide synthase (PKS) and subsequently undergoes condensation with diverse glycones [4]. The gene cluster controlling nogala- mycin biosynthesis has been identiﬁed and cloned [5, 6], and the literature reports the gene encoding the anthracene ring skeleton of nogalamycin [7, 8], allowing details of the nogalamycin biosynthesis pathway to be speculated. Previous research [8] suggested that the nogalamycin biosynthesis pathway can be divided into three phases: (I) the biosynthesis of aglycone (1-OH-nogalamycinone) with acetate as the chain initiation and extension unit; (II) the generation of TDP (thymidine diphosphate)-no- galamine and TDP-nogalose from 1-phosphate-D-glucose reactions: dehydrogenation, ammonia, via a series of the synthesis of methylation, and reduction; and III) Fig. 1 The nogalamycin biosynthesis pathway nogalamycin and its analogues from nogalamine, nogalose, and 1-OH-nogalamycinone in the presence of glycosyl transferases (Fig. 1).

With reference to the differences in structure and cura- tive effect among daunorubicin, 40-epi-daunorubicin, dox- the orubicin, aminotransferases encoded by dnrJ in Streptomyces coeruleorubidus and snogI in Streptomyces nogalater ATCC27451 have a similar function but inverse stereose- lectivity; therefore, a recombinant strain was constructed by replacing snogI with dnrJ for the purpose of obtaining nogalamycin analogues. Gene recombination was carried out according to standard protocols. The processes of genomic DNA and plasmid extraction from Streptomyces, preparative methods for competent cells and the transformation of Streptomyces, and Streptomyces-E.coli conjugation are described in great detail elsewhere [10]. The method used for gene detection by PCR targeting has been reported previously [11]. DNA sequencing was performed by Mapbioo lnc. (Shanghai, China). Primers were designed according to the genes snogI-L, snogI-R (GenBank: AF006633), and their neighboring sequences, as listed in Table 2. Brieﬂy, the full-length sequences of snogI-L, snogI-R, and dnrJ were ampliﬁed by PCR. Firstly, dnrJ was cloned into pBS to construct pLMX-3-80. DnrJ with ErmP was then transferred into pKC1139 as an EcoR I/Xba I fragment snogI-R was to generate pLMX-3-86. Subsequently, transferred into pLMX-3-86 as an Xba I/Hind III fragment to create pLMX-3-92. Finally, snogI-L was transferred into pLMX-3-92 as an Xba I/Xba I fragment to produce pLMX- 3-96. pLMX-3-96 was used to replace snogI in the S. nogalater chromosome. The accurate construction of the ﬁnal pLMX-3-96 plasmid was validated. Screening of the Recombinant Strain for Replacement of snogI with dnrJ

Escherichia coli ET12567 cells were transformed with the pLMX-3-96 plasmid, which were subsequently used as donors to transfer pLMX-3-96 into S. nogalater cells by conjugation. The successful conjugative transfer of plasmid DNA to E. coli ET12567 9 S. nogalater crosses has been previously described [12]. AmR transconjugants were selected and cultivated on TSB medium at 37 (cid:3)C for 5 days. This temperature is nonpermissive for the replication of pLMX-3-96 since it contains a temperature-sensitive replicon. Under these conditions, pLMX-3-96 would either be lost by the transconjugants or integrated into their chromosomes via homologous recombination. The pheno- types of the obtained strains were divided into three clas- ses: AmR transconjugants, obtained due to single crossover; Ams transconjugants, obtained due to double crossover; and Ams wild type S. nogalater. obtained due to loss of pLMX-3-96. A total of 42 Ams strains were

obtained. For further selection of the cells in which double crossover had occurred, we adopted a PCR screening method. If an Ams strain was obtained due to double crossover, its DNA would act as a template, and using For- dnrJ/Rev-dnrJ as primers, a fragment of approximately 1.3 kb (dnrJ) would be obtained. Conversely, if the strain was Ams wild type S. nogalater obtained due to loss of pLMX-3-96, no fragment would be detected by PCR. Among all those screened by PCR, 4 clones containing the dnrJ fragment (Fig. 5a) were obtained. Using the DNA of the recombinant strain mLMX-3-100 as a template and For-snogI-L/Rev-dnrJ as the primers, a fragment of approximately 2.8 kb was obtained, and using the same template and For-dnrJ/Rev-snogI-R as the primers, a fragment of approximately 2.2 kb was obtained (Fig. 5b). These results suggest that mLMX-3-100 likely originated from double crossover and contains the dnrJ gene in place of snogI. Culture of mLMX-3-100 and Detection and Analysis of Metabolites

The morphological characteristics of mLMX-3-100 were unlike those of the wild type strain Streptomyces nogalater ATCC27451; it did not produce spores on Gause I media, and the colour of the colonies was white rather than gray. Moreover, the phenotype of mLMX-3-100 can be stably inherited in as little as ﬁve transfers. The recombinant strain mLMX-3-100 was fermentation cultured under the same conditions as the wild type strain Streptomyces nogalater ATCC27451, and it was found that the colour of the fermentation liquor was gray rather than orange. The metabolites in the culture liquid were analyzed by HPLC, the results of which are shown in Fig. 6. HPLC revealed that mLMX-3-100 was incapable of producing nogalamy- cin, which was the main metabolite in the extracts obtained from wild type S. nogalater ATCC27451. These results indicate that the protein expression product of snogI plays an important role in nogalamycin biosynthesis; neverthe- less, contrary to our expectations, no epi-nogalamycin was produced. Possible reasons are that the transaminase expression product of dnrJ is unable to recognise the substrate or amino-isomerized nogalamine was generated but relevant glycosyl identiﬁed by the transferase. The antibacterial activity of the extract from the culture liquid of mLMX-3-100 was preliminarily evaluated against Bacillus subtilis using the paper disk method (Fig. 7). The metabolites of mLMX-3-100 did not inhibit the growth of the test culture, showing no antibacterial activity at all, which is likely due to the disruption of nogalamycin biosynthesis. The anthracyclines have multifunctional molecular struc- tures, and minor changes in the structure of the glycosyls around the chromophore can lead to signiﬁcant differences in their mechanism of action, pharmacokinetic toxicity, and antitumor activity [13]. With respect to the difference in and efﬁcacy among daunorubicin, 40-epi- structure daunorubicin, doxorubicin, and epirubicin, we used the daunomycin aminotransferase-encoding gene dnrJ to replace the nogalamycin aminotransferase-encoding gene snogI, the function of which is consistent with nogalamycin aminotransferase but the stereoselectivity is opposite, with a view to obtaining a nogalamycin analogue [14]. These data show that the recombinant strain mLMX-3- 100 disrupted the synthesis of nogalamycin; however, contrary to our predictions, no epi-nogalamycin was pro- duced. Possible reasons are that the aminotransferase expression product of dnrJ cannot recognise the substrate or amino-isomerized nogalamine was generated but cannot be identiﬁed by the relevant glycosyl transferase in the nogalamycin biosynthesis pathway. Nevertheless, the the protein the present study suggest results of expression product of the snogI gene plays a vital role in nogalamycin biosynthesis. Moreover, this research may provide a reference for further illustration of nogalamycin biosynthesis and its modiﬁcation by way of combinatorial biosynthesis.
